--- a/README.md
+++ b/README.md
@@ -58,12 +58,11 @@ Install as many bundles as you want — there's no overlap. A bundle only adds c
 
 ## Credentials
 
-Skills that need API keys (OpenAI, Notion, Telegram, etc.) ship an `env.example` file inside the plugin showing exactly which keys.
+Skills that need API keys declare them in `env.example` files inside the plugin. In Cowork there is no "project .env" — your keys live in ONE user-level file that every Genie skill falls back to:
 
-**Two ways to set credentials:**
+**`~/.claude/genie/.env`**
 
-1. **Vanilla Cowork (no Genie):** copy keys you need into your project's `.env`, or set them in your shell.
-2. **Inside a Genie repo:** run `python setup.py` (or `/genie-setup` mid-session) — it scans every installed plugin's `env.example` and concatenates them into a single `.env.example` at the repo root. Re-run after every install/update.
+To build it, install `genie-essentials@genie` (CLI marketplace) and say *"set up my keys"* — the `genie-setup-lite` skill aggregates every installed plugin's declared keys into `~/.claude/genie/.env.example`, seeds `~/.claude/genie/.env`, and appends new keys after updates. Fill in only what you use; the same file also serves Claude Code CLI, Codex, and Hermes. (genie-aios users: `/genie-setup` links this file to your repo's `.env` automatically.)
 
 `.env` files should always be gitignored.
 
